article.description:
Dirk Nowitzki had 25 points as the Mavericks beat the Wizards 103-97 Wednesday
night to take over the best record in the Western Conference.
article.headline: Mavs beat Wizards, take over as best in West
article.linkText: Mavs beat Wizards, take over as best in West
article.story:
DALLAS (AP) -- The Dallas Mavericks are right where they want to be. Not now, but in two months when it's time for the playoffs. Dallas goes into the All-Star break with the best record in the Western Conference, alone on top after a 103-97 victory over the Washington Wizards on Wednesday night. "That doesn't mean anything right now. That's where we want to be in April," Jason Terry said. "We're going to come back hungry. We know what we're playing for. ... We have to get home court." To get the No. 1 seed that would give them home-court advantage, the Mavericks (41-11) know they have to stay ahead of San Antonio in the Southwest Division. Or they can be no better than a No. 4 seed. "We're really striving to be the top dog in June, not February," coach Avery Johnson said. Dirk Nowitzki had 25 points with a key assist after the Wizards got within a point for the fourth time in the fourth quarter, 97-96 with 1:14 left after Caron Butler's 10-foot baseline jumper. After Butler's shot, the last field goal for Washington, the Mavericks crossed midcourt, called timeout and set their play. Erick Dampier, just back in the game, got a pass from Nowitzki and drove the lane for an easy layup with 53 seconds left. The Mavericks went ahead to stay with a 10-0 run midway through the second quarter, but in the closing minutes had to hold off the Wizards, who have lost two in a row since their season-best five-game winning streak. "We stopped them when we had to," Terry said. "That's the sign of a good team." The Mavericks won their 11th straight home game, one short of the franchise record. They play their first four games after the break at home. With San Antonio (40-12) losing 103-100 in overtime at Philadelphia in its last game before the break Wednesday night, the Mavs took over the top spot in the Western Conference. Only Eastern Conference-leading Detroit (42-9) has a better record. Since last losing at home Dec. 30 against Golden State, the Mavericks are 20-3 overall. That stretch included an NBA-best 13-game winning streak that was snapped Friday night at Denver. Following the Dampier layup, Gilbert Arenas missed another shot in what was one of the All-Star's worst shooting games of the season. Terry then drove for a layup to make it 101-96. Arenas finished with 12 points -- his third-lowest total this season and nearly 17 below his season average. He was 4-of-22 shooting. "That was difficult. I just tried to play my game and go inside," Arenas said. "It was kind of frustrating, driving in and getting hit. I didn't hear any whistle." With about 8 minutes left, Butler had a steal and passed to Arenas, who missed a layup while making contact in the air with defenders. No foul was called, and coach Eddie Jordan was given a technical foul after he ran to midcourt shouting his displeasure at the non-call. Nowitzki missed the free throw, but after the inbound pass hit an 18-footer. Arenas was initially left off the Eastern Conference All-Star team despite being the NBA's fourth-leading scorer. Commissioner David Stern put him on the squad last week to replace injured Jermaine O'Neal. This game wasn't reflective of what Arenas has done all season. He missed all seven of his shots in the fourth quarter. Plus, Nowitzki beat him on a drive with about 4 minutes left, turning around Arenas and popping an 11-foot jumper to make it 92-85. With 2:20 left and the Wizards within three, Arenas was called for an offensive foul on a drive against Nowitzki. The Mavericks couldn't convert and Butler drove the baseline for a layup to make it 97-96. Next was Nowitzki's pass to Dampier. Josh Howard scored 26 points and Terry added 19 for the Mavericks. Butler led the Wizards with 27 points and 11 rebounds, and Antawn Jamison added 24 points and 11 rebounds. Johnson, 57-13 since replacing the retired Don Nelson last March, will coach the Western Conference All-Stars in Houston on Sunday. The only Dallas player with him will be Nowitzki, who was selected last week as a reserve. The Mavericks' go-ahead run midway through the second quarter snapped a 36-all tie. Marquis Daniels found Howard alone under the basket for an easy slam dunk for the tiebreaking basket with 7:32 left, and Howard scored the next bucket on a layup after rebounding his own miss. Arenas missed three shots in that 3½-minute span.

Game notes
The game was tied 29-all after one, marking the first time in 16 home games that Dallas didn't outscore its opponent. ... During the game's first timeout, when he was recognized as the All-Star coach, Johnson never looked up from the huddle with his players, many of which joined in the ovation.
